{"title_page": "Aaron V. McAlvay", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n'''Aaron Vance McAlvay''' (July 19, 1847\u2013July 9, 1915) was a Justice of the [[Michigan Supreme Court]] from January 1, 1905 to July 9, 1915.<ref>[https://www.law.umich.edu/historyandtraditions/faculty/Faculty_Lists/Alpha_Faculty/Pages/AaronVMcAlvay.aspx University of Michigan faculty biography of Aaron V. McAlvay].</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]],<ref name=\"MSCHS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.micourthistory.org/justices/aaron-mcalvay/|title=Aaron McAlvey|publisher=Michigan Supreme Court Historical Society|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> McAlvay's father was a Michigan farmer, and the son spent most of his early life, when not in school, on the farm.<ref name=\"Memoriam\"/> He received his primary education in the common schools of Michigan, and received an [[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]] from the literary department of the [[University of Michigan]] in 1868, followed by an [[LL.B.]] from that institution in 1869.<ref name=\"Memoriam\">\"[http://www.micourthistory.org/special-sessions/in-memoriam-aaron-v-mcalvay/ In Memoriam Aaron V. Mcalvay]\", Michigan Supreme Court Historical Society (April 4, 1916).</ref>\n\nHe moved to [[Manistee, Michigan]], in October 1871, and immediately entered the practice of the law with Colonel S. W. Fowler. After the dissolution of that firm, McAlvay opened an office in Manistee and practiced alone until 1886, when he formed a partnership with the late John H. Grant, the firm name being McAlvay & Grant. This firm continued until McAlvay was appointed to a seat on the circuit court vacated by the death of Judge Harrison H. Wheeler. McAlvay was again appointed to the circuit court in 1901, to a seat vacated by the death of Judge Beardsley, serving until elected to the Michigan Supreme Court in November 1904. He took office on January 1, 1905, and was twice re-elected.<ref name=\"Memoriam\"/> He received the honorary degree of LL. D. in 1910.<ref name=\"Memoriam\"/>\n\nSoon after he became a member of the Supreme Court, McAlvay moved to Lansing, where he lived with his family until death. His wife, also a Michigan native, and five of his six children survived him.<ref name=\"Memoriam\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[List of justices of the Michigan Supreme Court|Justice of the Michigan Supreme Court]]\n|before=Newly established seat.\n|after=[[Rollin H. Person]]\n|years=1905\u20131915}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McAlvay, Aaron V.}}\n\n[[Category:Michigan Supreme Court justices]]\n\n\n{{Michigan-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n'''Aaron Vance McAlvay''' (July 19, 1847\u2013July 9, 1915) was a Justice of the [[Michigan Supreme Court]] from January 1, 1905 to July 9, 1915.<ref>[https://www.law.umich.edu/historyandtraditions/faculty/Faculty_Lists/Alpha_Faculty/Pages/AaronVMcAlvay.aspx University of Michigan faculty biography of Aaron V. McAlvay].</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]],<ref name=\"MSCHS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.micourthistory.org/justices/aaron-mcalvay/|title=Aaron McAlvey|publisher=Michigan Supreme Court Historical Society|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> McAlvay's father was a Michigan farmer, and the son spent most of his early life, when not in school, on the farm.<ref name=\"Memoriam\"/> He received his primary education in the common schools of Michigan, and received an [[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]] from the literary department of the [[University of Michigan]] in 1868, followed by an [[LL.B.]] from that institution in in 1869.<ref name=\"Memoriam\">\"[http://www.micourthistory.org/special-sessions/in-memoriam-aaron-v-mcalvay/ In Memoriam Aaron V. Mcalvay]\", Michigan Supreme Court Historical Society (April 4, 1916).</ref>\n\nHe moved to [[Manistee, Michigan]], in October 1871, and immediately entered the practice of the law with Colonel S. W. Fowler. After the dissolution of that firm, McAlvay opened an office in Manistee and practiced alone until 1886, when he formed a partnership with the late John H. Grant, the firm name being McAlvay & Grant. This firm continued until McAlvay was appointed to a seat on the circuit court vacated by the death of Judge Harrison H. Wheeler. McAlvay was again appointed to the circuit court in 1901, to a seat vacated by the death of Judge Beardsley, serving until elected to the Michigan Supreme Court in November 1904. He took office on January 1, 1905, and was twice re-elected.<ref name=\"Memoriam\"/> He received the honorary degree of LL. D. in 1910.<ref name=\"Memoriam\"/>\n\nSoon after he became a member of the Supreme Court, McAlvay moved to Lansing, where he lived with his family until death. His wife, also a Michigan native, and five of his six children survived him.<ref name=\"Memoriam\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[List of justices of the Michigan Supreme Court|Justice of the Michigan Supreme Court]]\n|before=Newly established seat.\n|after=[[Rollin H. Person]]\n|years=1905\u20131915}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McAlvay, Aaron V.}}\n\n[[Category:Michigan Supreme Court justices]]\n\n\n{{Michigan-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aaron_V._McAlvay"}
{"title_page": "List of Welsh people", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Lists of British people}}\nThis is a '''list of [[Welsh people]]''' ({{lang-cy|rhestr Cymry}}); an [[ethnic group]] and nation associated with [[Wales]].\n\nHistorian [[John Davies (historian)|John Davies]] argues that the origin of the Welsh nation can be traced to the late 4th and early 5th centuries, following the [[End of Roman rule in Britain|Roman departure from Britain]], although [[Brythonic languages|Brythonic]] or other [[Celtic languages]] seem to have been spoken in Wales since much earlier.<ref>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=John |authorlink=John Davies (historian) |title=A History of Wales |year=1994 |publisher=Penguin |page=54 |isbn=0-14-014581-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wales.ac.uk/Resources/Documents/Research/ODonnell.pdf| format=PDF |title=O'Donnell Lecture 2008 Appendix |year=2008|accessdate=10 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nThis list is for people of [[Welsh people|Welsh heritage and descent]], and for those otherwise perceived as Welsh; through either birth or adoption. Only those meeting [[WP:N|notability criteria]] are included. A few people appear in more than one section of the list.\n\n{{Expand list|date=October 2009}}\n\n==Actors==\n{{div col}}\n*[[Boyd Clack]] (born 1951), actor, writer, musician\n*[[Keith Allen (actor)|Keith Allen]] (born 1953)\n*[[Bennett Arron]] (born 1973), actor, comedian, writer\n*[[Stanley Baker]] (1927\u20131976)\n*[[Aneurin Barnard]] (born 1987)\n*[[Hywel Bennett]] (1944\u20132017)\n*[[David Bower]] (born 1969)\n*[[Rob Brydon]] (born 1965)\n*[[Richard Burton]] (1925\u20131984)\n*[[Richard Ian Cox]] (born 1973), actor, comedian and radio host\n*[[Timothy Dalton]] (born 1946)\n*[[Charles Danby]] (1858-1906), actor \n*[[Josie d'Arby]] (born 1973), actor, presenter\n*[[Gareth David-Lloyd]] (born 1981)\n*[[Garnon Davies]] (born 1982)\n*[[Phoebe Davies]] (1864\u20131912)\n*[[Richard Davies (actor)|Richard Davies]] (1926\u20132015)\n*[[Ryan Davies]] (1937\u20131977)\n*[[Windsor Davies]] (1930\u20132019)\n*[[Robert East (actor)|Robert East]] (born 1943)\n*[[Aimee-Ffion Edwards]] (born 1987)\n*[[Maudie Edwards]] (1906\u20131991)\n*[[Taron Egerton]] (born 1989)\n*[[Tom Ellis (actor)|Tom Ellis]] (born 1978)\n*[[Peg Entwistle]] (1908\u20131932)\n*[[Clifford Evans (actor)|Clifford Evans]] (1912\u20131985)\n*[[Luke Evans (actor)|Luke Evans]] (born 1979)\n*[[Pam Ferris]] (born 1948)\n*[[Huw Garmon]] (born 1966)\n*[[Colin George]] (born 1929)\n*[[Mali Harries]] (born 1976)\n*[[Matthew Gravelle]] (born 1976)\n*[[Hugh Griffith]] (1912\u20131980)\n*[[Kenneth Griffith]] (1921\u20132006)\n*[[Ioan Gruffudd]] (born 1973)\n*[[Edmund Gwenn]] (1875\u20131958)\n*[[Mike Gwilym]] (born 1949)\n*[[Robert Gwilym]] (born 1956)\n*[[Lyn Harding]] (1867\u20131952)\n*[[Doris Hare]] (1905\u20132000)\n*[[Richard Harrington (actor)|Richard Harrington]] (born 1975)\n*[[Georgia Henshaw]] (born 1993)\n*[[Anthony Hopkins]] (born 1937)\n*[[Donald Houston]] (1923\u20131991)\n*[[Glyn Houston]] (born 1926)\n*[[Aneirin Hughes]] (born 1958)\n*[[Gareth Hughes]] (1894\u20131965)\n*[[Nerys Hughes]] (born 1941)\n*[[Rhys Ifans]] (born 1968)\n*[[Emrys James]] (1928\u20131989)\n*[[Hywel John]] (born c.1970), more notable as a playwright\n*[[Margaret John]] (1926\u20132011)\n*[[Glynis Johns]] (born 1923)\n*[[Mervyn Johns]] (1899\u20131992)\n*[[Gary Jones (actor)|Gary Jones]] (born 1958)\n*[[Ruth Jones (actress)|Ruth Jones]] (born 1967)\n*[[Terry Jones]] (1942\u20132020)\n*[[Eddie Ladd]], also a contemporary dancer\n*[[Kate Lamb]]\n*[[Gwilym Lee]] (born 1983)\n*[[Desmond Llewelyn]] (1914\u20131999)\n*[[Bernard Lloyd]] (born 1934)\n*[[Philip Madoc]] (1934\u20132012)\n*[[Ruth Madoc]] (born 1943)\n*[[Steven Meo]] (born 1977)\n*[[Ray Milland]] (1907\u20131986)\n*[[Eve Myles]] (born 1978)\n*[[Kimberley Nixon]] (born 1985)\n*[[Jonny Owen]] (born 1971)\n*[[Kai Owen]] (born 1975)\n*[[Joanna Page]] (born 1978)\n*[[Si\u00e2n Phillips]]